==English==
===Etymology===
From Old (and modern) French [[vexer]], from Latin [[vexare|vēxāre]] ‘disturb, agitate’.

===Pronunciation===
*{{IPA|/vɛks/}}
*{{audio|en-us-vex.ogg|Audio (US)}}
*:Rhymes: [[Rhymes:English:-ɛks|-ɛks]]

===Verb===
{{en-verb|vex|es}}

#{{transitive}} To [[annoy]].
#:''Billy's professor was '''vexed''' by his continued failure to improve his grades.''
#{{transitive}} To cause (mental) suffering to; to [[distress]].

====Synonyms====
*(''to annoy''): [[agitate]], [[irritate]]
*(''to cause mental suffering''): [[afflict]], [[torment]]

====Derived terms====
*[[vexer]]
*[[vexingly]]
*[[vexation]]
*[[vexatious]]

